eenth century. Focusing on ongoing and shared concerns and social practices across the long nineteenth century, the book's thematically-organised sections mark major Transatlantic social movements of that era as expressed, negotiated, and recorded through literary production. The book offers a range of tools and texts for innovative thinking, teaching, and exploration. Headnotes provide guidance on how individual selections arose from social and historical contexts and, often, suggest potential pairings with other selections. Annotations create student-friendly identification of key terms or allusions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican literaturey19th century. 0aEnglish literaturey19th century. 0aSocial movements in literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / American / General.2bisacsh1 aHakimi-Hood, Heidi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHughes, Linda, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNemmers, Adam, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRobbins, Sarah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTaylor, Andrew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311078040640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781474429849zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474429849zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474429849/original  a978-3-11-078040-6 Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA